<treatment ID-GBIF-Taxon="182227967" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:E5C0C0D5BB9E5C6791EA49297402C9DD" httpUri="http://treatment.plazi.org/id/E5C0C0D5BB9E5C6791EA49297402C9DD" lastPageNumber="52" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<pageBreakToken pageId="51" pageNumber="52" start="start">5</pageBreakToken>
b. 
<taxonomicName LSID="E5C0C0D5-BB9E-5C67-91EA-49297402C9DD" authority="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus chinensis subsp. triangularis" order="Solanales" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="chinensis" status="subsp. nov." subSpecies="triangularis">Convolvulus chinensis subsp. triangularis J.R.I.Wood &amp; R.W.Scotland</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="51" pageNumber="52">subsp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">A subsp. typo habitu suberecta et foliis triangularibus.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus arvensis subsp. var. var. erectus" order="Solanales" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="arvensis" subSpecies="var." variety="erectus">Convolvulus arvensis var. erectus</taxonomicName>
Ledeb., Fl. Altaic. [Ledebour] 1: 224. 1829. (
<bibRefCitation author="Ledebour, CFvon" journalOrPublisher="Tableau encyclopedie et methodique" pageId="205" pageNumber="206" refId="B185" refString="Ledebour, CFvon, 1829. Flora Altaica volume." title="Flora Altaica volume" year="1829">Ledebour 1829</bibRefCitation>
: 225).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Type.</emphasis>
RUSSIA, Altai, Tiuguriuk stream by Katunja River (LE, not seen).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="type">
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
KAZAKHSTAN, &quot;in rupestribus montium Tarbagatai ad torrentium Dschanybek&quot;, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Karelin &amp; Kiriloff</emphasis>
328 (holotype LE ex Herb Ledebour!; isotypes BM001035796!, LE ex herb. Fischer!, LE ex herb. Schrenk!, P!).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="distinguishing features">
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Distinguishing features.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
Distinguished by its suberect habit and triangular leaves, c. 3-5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.5-4 cm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
Russia: Siberia (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Salefov</emphasis>
794, 806 (sin data), 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Mardovkin</emphasis>
s.n. (&quot;Siberia altaica&quot;), Kazakhstan (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Karelin &amp; Kiriloff</emphasis>
597 (&quot;Tarbagatai ad torrentium Dschanybek&quot;), 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Roldugin</emphasis>
s.n. [12/8/1960] &quot;Dzungarsky Alatai&quot;), 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Schrenk</emphasis>
s.n. (
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Songaria”">&quot;Songaria&quot;</normalizedToken>
). Apparently rare.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ker-Gawl., Bot. Reg. 4: t. 322. 1818. (Ker-Gawler" authorityYear="1818" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus chinensis" order="Solanales" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chinensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Convolvulus chinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most reliably distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 153. 1753. (Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus arvensis" order="Solanales" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arvensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Convolvulus arvensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the longer sepals. Additionally the auricles are often bifid, the central lobe oblong and the corolla usually deep pink and slightly larger than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 153. 1753. (Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus arvensis" order="Solanales" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arvensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Convolvulus arvensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is often considered to be a form of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 153. 1753. (Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus arvensis" order="Solanales" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arvensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Convolvulus arvensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but intermediates are uncommon, mainly being found in the Tibet region, and could be of hybrid origin. Molecular studies (
<bibRefCitation author="Williams, BRM" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="214" pageNumber="215" pagination="1287 - 1306" publicationUrl="10.12705/636.9" refId="B388" refString="Williams, BRM, Mitchell, TC, Wood, JRI, Harris, DJ, Scotland, RW, Carine, MA, 2014. Integrating DNA barcode data in a monograph of Convolvulus L. Taxon 63: 1287 - 1306, DOI: 10.12705/636.9" title="Integrating DNA barcode data in a monograph of Convolvulus L." url="10.12705/636.9" volume="63" year="2014">Williams et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
) strongly support the recognition of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ker-Gawl., Bot. Reg. 4: t. 322. 1818. (Ker-Gawler" authorityYear="1818" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus chinensis" order="Solanales" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chinensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Convolvulus chinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a distinct species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
